# Rebase Only Merged Agents

When rebasing after a merge, **only rebase the agents whose branches you just merged**. Do not rebase agents that are still running.

## Rule

After merging `agentN/ready` into main and pushing:

```bash
# Rebase ONLY the merged agent(s), not all four
cd ~/projects/APAS-VERUS-agent2
git fetch && git rebase origin/main && git push origin agent2/ready --force-with-lease
```

Do NOT run `scripts/rebase-agents.sh` unless you are certain all agents are idle.

## The Stash Test

If you find yourself needing to `git stash` in an agent worktree before rebasing, **STOP**. That means the agent has uncommitted work, which means it is probably running an active session. Stashing and rebasing under a running agent corrupts its working state.

**If you have to stash, you are breaking something.** Ask the user first.

## Why

- Agent worktrees may have active Claude sessions editing files.
- `git stash` + `git rebase` + `git push --force` yanks the working tree out from under a running session.
- The session sees its files disappear or change, leading to corrupted edits and lost work.
- `scripts/rebase-agents.sh` rebases ALL agents indiscriminately. Only use it when all agents are confirmed idle.
